import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>The Perqed solver architecture was not designed in isolation; rather, it evolved as a series of structural responses to specific computational bottlenecks encountered during exploratory benchmarking.</p>

<h2>Analysis of Search Stagnation</h2>

<p>During our evaluation of $R(4,6) \ge 36$—a recognized lower bound in Ramsey Theory—we utilized Simulated Annealing (SA) to identify a 2-coloring of the edges of $K_{35}$ without monochromatic $K_4$ or $K_6$ subgraphs. Despite extensive computation across multiple workers and billions of iterations, the search consistently reached an energy plateau of $E = 12$.</p>

<p>The persistence of this plateau across various seeds and cooling schedules indicated a structural limitation within the search space, rather than a failure of the heuristic search parameters.</p>

<h2>Symmetry Reduction and Space Enumeration</h2>

<p>To optimize the search, we restricted the domain to <em>circulant graphs</em>, where the adjacency relation is determined by the circular distance between vertices. For $N=35$, this reduced the search space from $2^{595}$ to $2^{17}$—approximately 131,072 states. This reduction allowed for a more exhaustive evaluation of the circulant subspace.</p>

<p>Implementation of circulant-aware SA mutations showed marginal improvement but failed to reach $E = 0$. This suggested that a valid witness might not exist within the circulant class for this specific bound.</p>

<h2>Satisfiability Modulo Theories (SMT) Resolution</h2>

<p>To move beyond heuristic search, we integrated SMT solvers into the pipeline. Unlike stochastic search, SMT solvers like Z3 utilize Conflict-Driven Clause Learning (CDCL) to reason about the feasibility of a given set of constraints. For a search space of $2^{17}$ boolean variables, SMT resolution is highly efficient.</p>

<p>We encoded the $R(4,6)$ circulant problem into 17 boolean variables with clique constraints represented as SAT clauses. Z3 evaluated the model and returned a result of <strong>UNSAT</strong>.</p>

<h2>Interpreting UNSAT as a Formal Lemma</h2>

<p>The UNSAT result provides a definitive proof that no circulant 2-coloring exists for $K_{35}$ that satisfies the $R(4,6)$ requirements. This is a significant mathematical observation that should be preserved and utilized to inform subsequent search strategies.</p>

<p>Previously, our search process was stateless, meaning the ARCHITECT lacked awareness of prior results and might redundantly explore falsified subspaces. To address this, we implemented a persistent state management system to capture and utilize these formal observations.</p>

<h2>The Hub-and-Spoke Architecture</h2>

<p>We introduced the <strong>ResearchJournal</strong> as the central Hub of our architecture. It serves as a typed, persistent repository for lemmas, observations, and falsified conjectures. Before initiating a new strategy, the ARCHITECT consults the Hub to refine its context with established knowledge:</p>

<pre><code>### PREVIOUSLY ESTABLISHED LEMMAS & OBSERVATIONS ###
- [LEMMA] No circulant 2-coloring of K_35 witnesses R(4,6)
  (Evidence: Z3 UNSAT: 17-var encoding, circulant 2^17 space exhausted)
- [OBSERVATION] SA on K_35 R(4,6) converged at E_min=12
  (Evidence: 500,000,000 iters × 8 workers)</code></pre>

<h2>The Integrated Solver Stack</h2>

<p>The resulting architecture leverages specialized tools for distinct sub-problems, coordinated through a central Hub:</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Layer</th><th>Tool</th><th>Role</th><th>Architectural Context</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Formulation</td><td>LLM (Gemini)</td><td>Conjecture translation to search configuration</td><td>Initial Hub-Spoke coordination</td></tr>
<tr><td>Exploration</td><td>Simulated Annealing</td><td>Heuristic search over high-dimensional spaces</td><td>Primary stochastic spoke</td></tr>
<tr><td>Resolution</td><td>Z3 (SMT)</td><td>Exhaustive verification of constrained subspaces</td><td>Deterministic verification spoke</td></tr>
<tr><td>Certification</td><td>Lean 4</td><td>Formal verification of proposed results</td><td>Formal proof kernel</td></tr>
<tr><td>State Management</td><td>ResearchJournal</td><td>Persistence of intermediate results and lemmas</td><td>The Central Hub</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>By delegating tasks to the most appropriate tool—SA for unconstrained exploration, Z3 for exact resolution, and Lean 4 for formal certification—the system maintains a high degree of rigor while optimizing computational resources. The ResearchJournal transforms isolated search attempts into a cumulative knowledge base, facilitating a more informed and efficient proof-discovery process.</p>

<h2>Future Directions</h2>

<p>The identification of the circulant subspace as UNSAT narrows the search for an $R(4,6)$ witness. Our current objective is to utilize the ARCHITECT to explore alternative structures, such as partial symmetries or MaxSAT-driven energy bounds, while maintaining the rigor of the Hub-and-Spoke model.</p>

<hr>

<p><em>Perqed is an open-source project. <a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed">View the source on GitHub</a> or <a href="/minutiae/">monitor the solver's real-time execution</a>.</em></p>
`;
